	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES games with the best animation</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />R-Type 1-3 actually use a single point for the ship's hitbox. Despite how hard these games can be, they're actually pretty forgiving in a couple of aspects like this. I don't know why I felt like sharing that.<br /><br />Anyway, I'm just curious, but is the player have its own designated spot in the object table so it's easy to look for? For collisions, I just thought of having the position of the player being one point, and have the hitbox have a separate position relative to the player coordinates. That way, if you crouch, the coordinates for the player don't have to move, only the hitbox. This is important because if you where crouching and then decided to jump, the player would start out partially through the floor, and could lead to you clipping through it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


